[3] Japan: Pneumonia in young people
Date: Mon 19 Apr 2021
Source: Mainichi Shimbun [in Japanese, machine trans. abridged, edited]
https://mainichi.jp/articles/20210419/k00/00m/040/182000c


A survey by Wakayama Prefecture revealed that the rate of pneumonia among people in their 20s and 40s who were infected with a mutant strain in Wakayama Prefecture due to a new type of coronavirus infection has doubled compared to conventional strains. Severe cases of the same age have also appeared in mutant strains, and Takako Nojiri, director of the Prefectural Health and Welfare Department, said: "It shows a high risk of aggravation of mutant strains. Young people also need to be careful."

Of those infected during the month from 14 Mar 2021, which the prefecture designated as the "4th wave" of infection, 363 were screened for mutant strain infections, of which 205 (56.5). %) were confirmed. We compared and analyzed the symptoms of 207 people, including these 205 people, the remaining 158 people infected with the conventional strain, and 49 related positives, estimated to be the conventional strain.

The proportion of people with pneumonia was 41.5% (86 people) for the conventional strain and 40.5% (83 people) for the mutant strain, which was not much different overall. However, when compared between the age groups in their 20s and 40s, the conventional strain was 22.6% (14 out of 62 people), while the mutant strain was 43.3% (42 out of 97 people), which was about 20 points higher. Looking at the number of people by age group, the number of conventional strains was 30 for people in their 70s, while the number of mutant strains was 19 in people in their 40s, followed by 15 in people in their 20s and 50s, and many in the young and middle age group.

Furthermore, there were 10 people in their 20s and 40s who needed oxygen administration, which the prefecture considers to be a seriously ill person. The severity rate in 40-year-olds was 18.4%, and that in 30-year-olds was 13.3%, which was higher than for those in their 60s (11.1%). There are no seriously ill people in their 20s and 40s with conventional strains, and the prefecture said: "We will continue to accumulate data and analyze it.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Kunihiko Iizuka

[The variant strain is not defined but thought to be N501Y (KI).

The report is translated as "people in their 20s and 40s," which I must assume should read 20s-40s.

This is an important finding to disseminate to emphasize the vulnerability of young people, and not only old people, to severe disease, particularly from the more transmissible variants. - Mod.LK]

